body:
It'd be great if propTypes had a property that gave vision into the expectations. This would allow easily generating documentation without parsing the code, which is easier and allows flexibility like reusing propType shapes, etc. It also helps with test automation / coverage reports.

Also related, a .note method on propTypes would allow better error messages, documentation, and coverage report output, and static analysis error messages e.g. in flow.

``` js
class Foo extends React.Component {
  static propTypes = {
    name: PropTypes.string.isRequired
      .note('The user\'s full name'),
    color: PropTypes.oneOf(['red', 'green', 'blue']),
    car: PropTypes.shape({
      model: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
      make: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
    }),
  };
  // ...
};
```

| expression | result |
| --- | --- |
| `Foo.propTypes.name.meta.type` | `'string'` |
| `Foo.propTypes.name.meta.note` | `'The user\'s full name'` |
| `Foo.propTypes.color.meta.type` | `'oneOf'` |
| `Foo.propTypes.color.meta.variants` | `['red', 'green', 'blue']` |
| `Foo.propTypes.car.meta.shape.model.meta.type` | `'string'` |

Why react core? I started writing a library that does this, but I realized that tools like flow require you to use react's propTypes.  This would be a non-breaking change, and I think it adds a moderate amount of value.
